      "result": "\u003coutput\u003e\n{\n  \"rating\": 4,\n  \"summary\": \"Clean, focused frontend change. `IntegrationIcon` correctly renders /public-served SVGs with a reasonable fallback; SVG assets are hygienic (viewBox, role=img, title, no scripts/external refs, no baked dimensions). Moving the Add button out of `PageHeader.actions` is actually consistent — none of the other 5 pages using `PageHeader` populate `actions`, so this page is now aligned with the rest. Only minor a11y polish needed on the fallback element.\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"gui/src/components/integrations/integration-icon.tsx:28-35\",\n      \"issue\": \"Fallback uses `aria-label` on a generic `\u003cdiv\u003e` (no `role`). Screen readers may or may not announce `aria-label` on a non-semantic element, and the visible initials (`type.slice(0,2)`) plus the label produce inconsistent output (visible 'cu' vs. announced 'custom icon'). Also: when an unknown type lands here, the user sees only the first two characters with no other affordance.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add `role=\\\"img\\\"` to the fallback `\u003cdiv\u003e` so AT consistently treats it as a labeled image, OR drop the aria-label and let the visible text be the accessible name. Consider logging a console.warn in dev when an unmapped type is rendered, so new backend integration types don't silently regress to initials.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"gui/src/components/integrations/integration-icon.tsx:3-11\",\n      \"issue\": \"`ICON_PATHS` is a hand-maintained string map with no compile-time link to the canonical `IntegrationType` union/enum in `@/lib/types`. If a new backend integration type ships, the GUI silently falls back to two-letter initials with no test failure.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Either type the keys as `Record\u003cIntegrationType, string\u003e` (forces TS to surface missing entries) or add a test that iterates the known integration types from the type module and asserts each has an icon.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"gui/src/components/integrations/integration-icon.tsx:42-49\",\n      \"issue\": \"`width={size}` / `height={size}` set as HTML attrs while consumers may also pass `className` with sizing utilities (e.g. `w-6 h-6`). CSS wins, so this works, but `style={{width:size,height:size}}` would match the fallback branch and remove the inconsistency between the two code paths.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Either inline-style both branches or attribute-style both; keep the two visual branches symmetric so changes to one don't drift.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"gui/src/components/integrations/integration-icon.test.tsx:21-24\",\n      \"issue\": \"Only one assertion on the fallback (text content). Missing coverage: (a) that the fallback has an accessible role for AT, (b) that the `size` prop correctly threads through to width/height on the rendered img.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add a `size={32}` assertion and an a11y assertion (`getByRole('img', { name: 'custom icon' })` once role=img is added to the fallback).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"gui/public/integration-icons/notion.svg\",\n      \"issue\": \"Notion mark is `fill=\\\"#000000\\\"`. Renders fine on the current `bg-white` card chip, but will be invisible if the chip ever inherits a dark theme. Other icons (github #181717) have the same risk to a lesser degree.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Either keep the white chip wrapper as a hard contract (already present in integration-card.tsx:30) or document it. If dark-mode theming is on the roadmap, swap to currentColor variants for monochrome marks.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"recommendations\": [\n    \"Add `role=\\\"img\\\"` to the fallback `\u003cdiv\u003e` in IntegrationIcon for consistent screen-reader announcement.\",\n    \"Type `ICON_PATHS` against the canonical `IntegrationType` union so new types break the build instead of silently falling back.\",\n    \"Extend the test to assert the `size` prop and the fallback's accessible role.\"\n  ],\n  \"metadata\": {\n    \"files_reviewed\": 11,\n    \"domain\": \"gui-routes (frontend)\"\n  }\n}\n\u003c/output\u003e",
